1. Confidentiality
Definition

Confidentiality is the process of protecting sensitive information from unauthorized access. It ensures that only authorized users can view or access data.

Why it is Important
Protects personal and confidential information.
Prevents data theft and privacy breaches.
Maintains customer and organizational trust.
Real-World Example

Online banking systems use usernames, passwords, and Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) to ensure only authorized users can access their accounts.

2. Integrity
Definition

Integrity ensures that data remains accurate, complete, and unchanged unless modified by an authorized user.

Why it is Important
Prevents unauthorized changes.
Ensures data accuracy.
Maintains trust in information.
Real-World Example

Universities protect student marks so that only authorized staff can modify examination results.

3. Availability
Definition

Availability ensures that systems, applications, and data are accessible whenever authorized users need them.

Why it is Important
Prevents downtime.
Supports business continuity.
Allows users to access services without interruption.
Real-World Example

Cloud storage services maintain backup servers so users can access files even if one server fails.

Comparison Table
Principle	Definition	Importance	Example
Confidentiality	Protects data from unauthorized access	Prevents data leaks	Online Banking
Integrity	Keeps data accurate	Prevents unauthorized modifications	Student Results
Availability	Ensures systems remain accessible	Prevents downtime	Cloud Storage